item.title: Housing data brightens U.S. economic growth outlook
item.description: WASHINGTON (Reuters) - Permits for future U.S. home construction hit a near 5-1/2 year-high in October and prices for single-family homes notched big gains in September, suggesting a run-up in mortgage interest rates has not derailed the housing recovery.

item.title: At least 10 Haitians die, 110 saved from capsized ship in Bahamas
item.description: NASSAU, Bahamas (Reuters) - At least 10 Haitian migrants were killed and 110 were rescued after clinging to the hull and mast of an overloaded wooden sloop that capsized in the Bahamas, U.S. and Bahamian officials said on Tuesday.

item.title: Ukraine leader to go to EU summit, but not ready to sign pact
item.description: KIEV (Reuters) - Ukrainian President Viktor Yanukovich said on Tuesday he would attend an EU summit this week, but, criticizing the bloc for a 'humiliating' financial aid offer, declared he would sign a free trade pact only when it suited Ukraine's interests.

item.title: Exclusive: U.N. says Syria combatants stymie aid effort
item.description: GENEVA (Reuters) - The United Nations says its aid convoys cannot reach around 250,000 people in areas besieged by Syrian government forces or rebels, despite "growing needs and intensifying conflict".

item.title: Defying China, U.S. aircraft fly over East China Sea without notification
item.description: WASHINGTON (Reuters) - Two unarmed U.S. B-52 bombers on a training mission flew over disputed islands in the East China Sea without informing Beijing, Pentagon officials said on Tuesday, defying China's declaration of a new airspace defense zone in the region.

item.title: Referendum on Egypt's constitution seen in December
item.description: CAIRO (Reuters) - Egypt will hold a referendum on an amended constitution in December, the group drafting it said on Tuesday, an important step in an army-backed roadmap meant to lead to elections.

item.title: EU demands protection against U.S. data surveillance
item.description: BRUSSELS (Reuters) - The European Commission called on Tuesday for new protection for Europeans under United States' law against misuse of personal data, in an attempt to keep in check the U.S. surveillance revealed by former NSA contractor Edward Snowden.

item.title: Supreme Court to hear Obamacare contraception cases
item.description: WASHINGTON (Reuters) - The U.S. Supreme Court agreed on Tuesday to consider religious objections made by corporations to a provision of President Barack Obama's healthcare law that requires employers to provide health insurance that covers birth control.

item.title: Bombers north of Baghdad kill eight soldiers
item.description: BAGHDAD (Reuters) - Two suicide bombers killed eight Iraqi soldiers and wounded 26 near an army headquarters north of Baghdad on Tuesday, police and medical sources said.

item.title: Italian prosecutor seeks total 30 years sentence for Amanda Knox
item.description: FLORENCE, Italy (Reuters) - An Italian prosecutor asked for a total sentence of 30 years for American student Amanda Knox on Tuesday in a retrial for the murder of her British roommate Meredith Kercher.

item.title: Battle lines drawn as Scotland unveils independent future
item.description: GLASGOW, Scotland (Reuters) - The Scottish government unveiled its long-awaited vision for independence on Tuesday, promising Scots they could forge their own prosperity but keep the pound and the queen if they vote next year to end a 306-year-old union with England.

item.title: Hardliners hold fire on Iran nuclear deal, but for how long?
item.description: DUBAI (Reuters) - Iran's nuclear negotiators returned home as heroes on Sunday, greeted by jubilant supporters after securing a deal with world powers over the country's disputed atomic program.

item.title: UK court hears celebrity chef Nigella Lawson took drugs -reports
item.description: LONDON (Reuters) - Two kitchen assistants who used to work for British celebrity chef Nigella Lawson have alleged that she was a regular user of cocaine and other drugs, according to reports of a court hearing published by several national British media on Tuesday.

item.title: Japanese airlines to stop giving China flight plans through new zone
item.description: TOKYO (Reuters) - Japan's two biggest airlines have bowed to a government request to stop filing flight plans demanded by China on routes through a new Chinese air defense zone, whose creation has ratcheted up tensions over the bitterly disputed region.

item.title: Oil workers strike over insecurity in Libya's Benghazi
item.description: TRIPOLI (Reuters) - Oil workers, civil servants and private sector staff went on strike in the Libyan port city of Benghazi on Tuesday, protesting against deteriorating security a day after deadly clashes there between the army and Islamist militants.

item.title: Egypt referendum seen in December: official
item.description: CAIRO (Reuters) - A referendum on Egypt's amended constitution will be held in December, the spokesman of the constituent assembly said on Tuesday, an important step towards elections.

item.title: Iran says nuclear deal makes oil exports smoother, cheaper
item.description: DUBAI (Reuters) - Iran's nuclear deal with the West will make it easier, cheaper and less stressful to trade its oil, thanks largely to a partial lifting of the European shipping insurance ban, a senior Iranian industry official said on Tuesday.

item.title: India state examines snooping allegation against PM candidate Modi
item.description: NEW DELHI (Reuters) - A state governed by Indian opposition candidate for prime minister Narendra Modi has launched an investigation into allegations he ordered invasive surveillance of an architect, in a case his opponents say shows a tendency to abuse power.

item.title: Thai protesters step up campaign to oust government
item.description: BANGKOK (Reuters) - Thousands of protesters surrounded Thailand's Interior Ministry and forced the evacuation of four others on Tuesday, intensifying their campaign to bring down the government of Prime Minister Yingluck Shinawatra.

item.title: Iraq says no success tracing killers of Iranian dissidents
item.description: BAGHDAD (Reuters) - Iraq is hunting militants, still unidentified, who led a deadly attack on an Iranian dissident camp near Baghdad and dismisses suggestions its own security forces were behind the violence, a senior government official said.

item.title: Once-bitten Sharif to appoint new Pakistani army chief
item.description: ISLAMABAD (Reuters) - Pakistan's prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, will this week name a new army chief who, if all goes well, could help the nuclear-armed nation shake off a legacy of coups and instability.

item.title: 11 Pakistani teachers kidnapped during polio campaign released: officials
item.description: PESHAWAR, Pakistan (Reuters) - Militants released on Tuesday 11 teachers who had been kidnapped in Pakistan's lawless northwest during a polio vaccination campaign last week, local officials said.

item.title: Indian dentist couple handed life sentence for killing daughter
item.description: NEW DELHI (Reuters) - An Indian court sentenced a dentist couple to life in prison on Tuesday for the murder of their 14-year-old daughter and a Nepalese servant five years ago, concluding a sensational trial that has sharply divided public opinion.

item.title: Independent Scotland would keep the pound and the queen, says Salmond
item.description: GLASGOW, Scotland (Reuters) - An independent Scotland would keep the British pound, the queen and remain in the European Union but have its own defense force and collect its own taxes, First Minister Alex Salmond said on Tuesday.

item.title: Two Swedish journalists missing in Syria
item.description: STOCKHOLM (Reuters) - Sweden is investigating the disappearance of two Swedish journalists who are missing in Syria, the Foreign Ministry said on Tuesday.
